{{基礎情報 公家|氏名=倭手彦|画像=|画像サイズ=|画像説明=|時代=[[上古#日本|上古]]・[[古墳時代]]|生誕=不明|死没=不明|改名=|諡号=|神号=|戒名=|墓所=|官位=[[倭国造]]|主君=[[欽明天皇]]|氏族=[[倭氏|倭直]]|父母=|兄弟=|妻=|子=}}'''Yamato no Tehiko''' (year of birth and death unknown ) was a {{ill|Gōzoku|lt=powerful|en}} clan leader in [[Kofun period|the Kofun period]] and one of '''[[Yamato no Kuni no Miyatsuko|the Wa kuni no miyatsuko]]''' . His Kabane was {{ill|10=ja|11=大葉子|直 (姓)|Atai}}

== Origin ==
The Wa clan (Wa koku no [[Yamato no Kuni no Miyatsuko|miyatsuko family]] ) was a powerful clan in [[Yamato Province|Yamato-go]], Joka - gun, Yamato Province, which currently corresponds to Yamato, Saho-cho, in the southern part of [[Tenri, Nara|Tenri City]], [[Nara Prefecture]] . The {{ill|Shinsen Shōjiroku|en}} 's "Yamato no Kuni Kamiwake" section states that "his descendants were Kamichitsuhiko no Mikoto," while [[Nihon Shoki|the Nihon Shoki]], Volume 3 states that his ancestor was {{ill|Saonetsuhiko|lt=Shiinetsuhiko|fr}} <ref>『日本書紀』神武天皇即位前紀甲寅年10月5日条</ref>, and the [[Kojiki]] states that his ancestor was {{ill|Saonetsuhiko|fr}} <ref>『古事記』中巻、神武天皇条</ref> .
{{Short description|Japanese noble family}}{{Infobox Japanese clan|province of origin=[[Yamato Province]]|home province=[[Yamato Province]]|image=Ohyamato-jinja Haiden.jpg|image caption=Oyamato Shrine, their main shrine|founder={{ill|Shinetsuhiko|ja|椎根津彦}},<br> {{ill|Ichishi no Nagaochi|ja|市磯長尾市}}}}
Their [[Ujigami]] or clan god is [[Yamato Okunitama]] of [[Ōyamato Shrine]]<ref>{{Cite web|title=International Symposium "Perspectives on Japanese history and literature from ancient historical records"|url=https://www.waseda.jp/inst/sgu/news-en/2019/04/12/5171|access-date=2023-05-04|website=Top Global University Project: Waseda Goes Global|language=en}}</ref> Some scholars interpret the ''kami'' as being a variant or epithet of [[Ōmononushi]] who has much more widespread worship.<ref name="Ellwood-1990">{{Cite journal|last=Ellwood|first=Robert S.|date=1990|title=The Sujin Religious Revolution|journal=Japanese Journal of Religious Studies|volume=17|issue=2/3|pages=199–217|doi=10.18874/jjrs.17.2-3.1990.199-217|issn=0304-1042|jstor=30234018|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_Q81DQAAQBAJ|title=Shinto: A History|last=Hardacre|first=Helen|date=2017|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-062171-1|language=en}}</ref>{{rp|22}} There is a complex myth about the origins of modern worship of [[Yamato Okunitama]] during the reign of [[Emperor Sujin]].<ref name="D-2012">{{Cite web|last=D|first=John|date=2012-11-10|title=Teeuwen on Shinto|url=https://www.greenshinto.com/2012/11/10/teeuwen-on-shinto/|access-date=2023-05-04|website=Green Shinto|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name="japanpolicy">https://www.japanpolicyforum.jp/pdf/2016/no35/DJweb_35_cul_02.pdf</ref><ref name="freidok">https://freidok.uni-freiburg.de/fedora/objects/freidok:4635/datastreams/FILE1/content</ref><ref name="Nihongi">{{Citation|title=Book V|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Nihongi:_Chronicles_of_Japan_from_the_Earliest_Times_to_A.D._697/Book_V|work=Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697, Volume 1|access-date=2023-05-04}}</ref>
[[ja:倭手彦]]
[[en:draft:Yamato no Tehiko]]
== History ==
[[File:Hibara-jinja,_torii_closeup.jpg|thumb|240x240px|[[Hibara Shrine]], at the foot of [[Mount Miwa]] in [[Sakurai, Nara]], identified as the place where the Yata-no-Kagami and the Kusanagi-no-Tsurugi were first enshrined after their removal from the imperial palace.]]
During [[Jimmu's Eastern Expedition]] {{ill|Saonetsuhiko|ja|椎根津彦}} was given the position of governor of [[Yamato Province]] by [[Emperor Jimmu]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Friday: Kojiki (「乞食」ではなく『古事記』ですヨ！！) #26|url=https://japaneseexperts.net/972/|access-date=2023-05-04|website=Japanese Experts Net|language=en-US}}</ref> And Saonetsuhiko became their ancestor.<ref>{{Cite web|date=2023-10-26|title=Saonetsuhiko {{!}} 國學院大學デジタルミュージアム|url=https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/id=9159|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20231026183115/https://d-museum.kokugakuin.ac.jp/eos/detail/id=9159|archive-date=2023-10-26|access-date=2023-12-04}}</ref>

There is a complex myth about the reign of [[Emperor Sujin]] and its link to the worship of [[Yamato Okunitama]] and [[Amaterasu]]. There was a crisis during his reign and eventually the worship of [[Amaterasu]] and [[Yamato Okunitama]] were moved out of the imperial palace to separate shrines.<ref name="D-2012" /><ref name="japanpolicy" /><ref name="freidok" /><ref name="Nihongi" />

Worship of Amaterasu moved to [[Hibara Shrine]] and then many other shrines called {{ill|Moto-Ise Shrines|lt=|ja|元伊勢}} until eventually reaching [[Ise Jingu]].<ref name="Ellwood-1990" />

By contrast the worship of [[Yamato Okunitama]] moved to [[Oyamato Shrine]], near [[Hibara Shrine]] and [[Omiwa Shrine]]. Yamato Okunitama was first entrusted to a daughter of [[Emperor Sujin]] named {{Ill|Nunaki-iri-hime|ja|渟名城入姫命}}, but shortly afterwards, her health began to fail. It is recorded that she became emaciated and lost all of her hair, which rendered her unable to perform her duties.<ref name="aston150–164">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_oEfAAAAYAAJ|title=Nihongi: Chronicles of Japan from the Earliest Times to A.D. 697, Volume 2|author=Aston, William George.|date=1896|publisher=The Japan Society London|isbn=9780524053478|pages=150–164|author-link=William George Aston}}</ref> These efforts still did not alleviate the ongoing plague, so Sujin decreed that a [[divination]] be performed sometime during the 7th year of his reign, that would involve him making a trip to the plain of Kami-asaji, and invoking the [[Yaoyorozu no Kami|eighty myriad deities]].<ref name="aston150–164" />

After the divination, {{ill|Ichishi no Nagaochi|ja|市磯長尾市}}, a descendant of {{ill|Shinetsuhiko|ja|椎根津彦}} would conduct the rites pertaining to Okunitama, replacing the emaciated Nunaki-iri-hime.<ref name="Ellwood-1990" /> {{ill|Ichishi no Nagaochi|ja|市磯長尾市}} would be the ancestor of the Yamato no Kuni no Miyatsuko.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Page:Nihongi by Aston.djvu/208|url=https://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Page:Nihongi_by_Aston.djvu/208|access-date=2023-10-24|website=en.wikisource.org|language=en}}</ref>

{{ill|Yamato no Agoko|lt=Agoko no Sukune|ja|倭吾子籠}} was a notable member of the clan and governor of Yamato Province<ref>{{Cite web|date=April 2022|title=Episode 61: Bad Behavior and the People that Excuse It|url=https://sengokudaimyo.com/podcast/episode-61|access-date=2023-05-04|website=Sengoku Daimyo|language=en-US}}</ref>



== record ==
In 562 AD (the 23rd year of [[Emperor Kinmei|Emperor Kinmei's reign]] ), after the Mimana government was destroyed by Silla <ref>『日本書紀』欽明天皇23年1月条</ref>, Emperor Kinmei fervently wished to restore {{ill|10=ja|11=任那日本府|lt2=任那日本府|the Mimana Nihonfu}}.

According to Volume 29 of the Nihon Shoki, [[681|in 681]] (April 10th year of [[Emperor Tenmu|Emperor Tenmu's reign]] ), a member of the clan, Yamato Naotatsumaro, was given the surname " {{ill|Muraji|en}} " <ref>『日本書紀』天武天皇10年4月12日条</ref>, and in September 12th year of Emperor Tenmu's reign, the surname "Muraji" was bestowed on all members of the Yamato clan. <ref>『日本書紀』天武天皇12年9月2日条</ref> With the establishment of the eight-rank system of surnames, in 685 (June 14th year of Emperor Tenmu's reign), the [[Kuni no miyatsuko|Yamato]] clan, a clan descended from [[Clan|the kuni]] no miyatsuko, was given the surname Ikimi . <ref>『日本書紀』天武天皇14年6月20日条</ref>

Volume 19 of the " [[Nihon Shoki]] " contains the story of {{ill|10=ja|11=紀男麻呂|lt2=紀男麻呂|Kino Omaro}}, the commander-in-chief of the army that conquered [[Silla]], and Kawabe no Nie. When Silla made a fake surrender, Otokomaro did not accept the invitation and stopped his advance, but Kyokan fought even harder and, not understanding the meaning of the white flag raised by the Silla side, also raised the white flag and advanced. As a result, the Silla side attacked again, causing heavy losses to the vanguard forces.

Wa no Kuni no Miyatsuko Tehiko, who had been fighting under Nenkan, decided that it was no longer possible to turn the tide of battle and withdrew from the front lines. The Silla warrior took up a spear and pursued him, cornering him in a ditch in the castle and throwing his spear at him, but Tehiko rode his swift horse over the ditch and barely escaped. The fighting general was so frustrated that he couldn't help but shout out loud.

It is unclear what became of Yamatohiko after that, as there is no record of it. <ref>『日本書紀』欽明天皇23年7月条</ref>

== Family tree ==
Many clans may be descendants of Furutama no Mikoto. This includes the {{ill|Owari clan|ja|尾張氏|en}} and [[Yamato no Kuni no Miyatsuko]]. This is a subject of debate.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160422190938/http://wwr2.ucom.ne.jp/hetoyc15/keihu/amabe/amabe-k2.htm|access-date=2023-12-13|website=web.archive.org}}</ref>
